to call her mother in
 public, only Laura,

531
00:30:25,060 --> 00:30:26,930
as if we were friends.

532
00:30:26,930 --> 00:30:29,640
-Well, you never seemed
 particularly interested in me

533
00:30:29,640 --> 00:30:30,140
as a mother.

534
00:30:30,140 --> 00:30:32,360
I thought perhaps you'd
 prefer me as a friend.

535
00:30:32,360 --> 00:30:34,170
-I had plenty of friends.

536
00:30:34,170 --> 00:30:36,710
-You certainly did, and you
 were with them all of the time.

537
00:30:36,710 --> 00:30:38,320
You never even came
 home on vacation.

538
00:30:38,320 --> 00:30:40,860
-Well, I wasn't ready
 to be paraded around

539
00:30:40,860 --> 00:30:43,220
as one of your precious
 little accessories.

540
00:30:43,220 --> 00:30:46,740
-You know, about a year
 after she'd gone to school,

541
00:30:46,740 --> 00:30:50,720
Atorian and I went to a party,
 and someone asked how she was.

542
00:30:50,720 --> 00:30:53,980
And I remember thinking, oh,
 oh, Nina, yes, that's right.

543
00:30:53,980 --> 00:30:55,820
I have a daughter.

544
00:30:55,820 --> 00:30:58,150
I'd put her clean
 out of my head.

545
00:30:58,150 --> 00:30:59,390
-Your life.

546
00:30:59,390 --> 00:31:01,610
-If we expect nothing
 from our children,

547
00:31:01,610 --> 00:31:04,620
and they expect nothing from
 us, nobody will be disappointed.

548
00:31:04,620 --> 00:31:06,900
-Hmm, only lonely.

549
00:31:06,900 --> 00:31:10,450
-It's very beautiful.

550
00:31:10,450 --> 00:31:14,810
One or another is lost since
 we fall apart endlessly,

551
00:31:14,810 --> 00:31:17,370
in one motion depart
 from each other.

552
00:31:20,130 --> 00:31:22,680
-D.H. Lawrence was
 Atorian's favorite poet.

553
00:31:22,680 --> 00:31:25,610
And that so sums up the
 way I feel about him.

554
00:31:25,610 --> 00:31:27,890
At least writing about him.

555
00:31:27,890 --> 00:31:32,390
How are we ever supposed to know
 what a person's really like?

556
00:31:32,390 --> 00:31:33,460
Maybe it's impossible.

557
00:31:33,460 --> 00:31:35,320
Maybe they just
 keep sliding away

558
00:31:35,320 --> 00:31:37,140
like water changing
 all the time.

559
00:31:37,140 --> 00:31:46,340
-To be celebrated is nothing,
 but to be loved is everything.

560
00:31:46,340 --> 00:31:51,540
-Oh, my mother was less inspired
 when my father passed away.

561
00:31:51,540 --> 00:31:54,550
She sent a card.

562
00:31:54,550 --> 00:31:57,320
-Well, I just had so
 little to say about him.

563
00:31:57,320 --> 00:32:02,020
I mean, the whole relationship
 was such a whirlwind,

564
00:32:02,020 --> 00:32:04,590
[FRENCH] I think
 you say in France.

565
00:32:04,590 --> 00:32:06,460
-[FRENCH] yes.

566
00:32:06,460 --> 00:32:10,260
-A sudden, exhilarating
 leap into the void.

567
00:32:10,260 --> 00:32:12,250
-Well, I should have looked.

568
00:32:12,250 --> 00:32:14,790
Within a year he had
 me under a pedestal.

569
00:32:14,790 --> 00:32:17,200
And in the end, the only
 thing that we had in common

570
00:32:17,200 --> 00:32:20,190
was Nina, which, of course,
 made it all worthwhile.

571
00:32:20,190 --> 00:32:24,430
Well, I must say it was
 fund while it lasted.

572
00:32:24,430 --> 00:32:26,560
I swear he had a
 hand with 20 fingers,

573
00:32:26,560 --> 00:32:28,040
and it was always on my ass.

574
00:35:41,750 --> 00:35:45,990
-I was going to spend the day
 at Wilbur Robinson's house.

575
00:35:45,990 --> 00:35:50,750
And Wilbur is my best
 friend, and his house

576
00:35:50,750 --> 00:35:53,780
is the greatest place
 in the world to visit.

577
00:35:59,510 --> 00:36:04,430
It's kind of dull around
 here today, said Wilbur.

578
00:36:04,430 --> 00:36:11,040
And I looked around, Aunt Billy
 was playing with her train set,

579
00:36:11,040 --> 00:36:14,200
cousin Pete was
 walking the cats.

580
00:36:14,200 --> 00:36:19,940
And Uncle Gaston sat comfortably
 in the family county.

581
00:36:19,940 --> 00:36:24,490
-It's so odd having
 a child, Lyle.

582
00:36:24,490 --> 00:36:25,790
I keep thinking when
 he learns to talk,

583
00:36:25,790 --> 00:36:27,790
he's going to tell me everything
 that's on that little mind,

584
00:36:27,790 --> 00:36:29,330
and I'm going to
 know him entirely.

585
00:36:32,620 --> 00:36:33,890
We never know anyone
 like that, do we?

586
00:36:33,890 --> 00:36:36,160
-How well did our
 parents know us?

587
00:36:40,010 --> 00:36:41,840
-But you'll tell Mommy what
 you're thinking, won't you?

588
00:36:41,840 --> 00:36:43,320
-Don't do it.

589
00:36:43,320 --> 00:36:43,820
-Huh?

590
00:36:43,820 --> 00:36:46,000
Tell me what's on your mind?

591
00:36:48,590 --> 00:36:51,280
Aw, are you thinking
 you're stinky?

592
00:36:51,280 --> 00:36:52,750
Because I do.

593
00:36:52,750 --> 00:36:55,320
Or are you thinking
 you want Uncle

594
00:36:55,320 --> 00:36:57,570
Lyle to change your
 diaper, are you?

595
00:36:57,570 --> 00:37:00,800
-Oh, there are limits to
 Uncle Lyle's devotion.

596
00:37:00,800 --> 00:37:07,150
-Oh, actually, he's warm.

597
00:37:07,150 --> 00:37:11,510
Here, just run this
 under some cold water.

598
00:37:11,510 --> 00:37:14,100
Hey, honey, hey.

599
00:37:14,100 --> 00:37:16,590
Hey.

600
00:37:16,590 --> 00:37:19,080
Hey.

601
00:37:19,080 --> 00:37:22,070
-Here you go.

602
00:37:22,070 --> 00:37:23,560
-Hello, happy one.

603
00:37:30,030 --> 00:37:32,250
-You know, towards
 the end, I used

604
00:37:32,250 --> 00:37:35,880
to pray that Tony's
 illness would just turn him

605
00:37:35,880 --> 00:37:37,180
into a baby, and
 then he wouldn't

606
00:37:37,180 --> 00:37:40,410
know what was happening to him.

607
00:37:40,410 --> 00:37:41,320
-But he did.

608
00:37:44,210 --> 00:37:46,620
That's what he wanted.

609
00:37:46,620 --> 00:37:48,500
-I never knew what Tony wanted.

610
00:37:53,670 --> 00:37:55,630
It should be easier than
 changing a grown man,

611
00:37:55,630 --> 00:37:56,270
don't you think?

612
00:38:01,390 --> 00:38:06,170
-I think I'm more afraid of
 being sick than I am of dying.

613
00:38:06,170 --> 00:38:08,570
It's too abstract for me.

614
00:38:08,570 --> 00:38:12,830
I can't imagine
 dying or being dead.

615
00:38:12,830 --> 00:38:16,910
But I can imagine being sick.

616
00:38:16,910 --> 00:38:18,060
I don't mind dying,
 you see, it's

617
00:38:18,060 --> 00:38:21,700
just the preliminaries I hate.

618
00:38:21,700 --> 00:38:25,310
I can feel it coming, I think.

619
00:38:25,310 --> 00:38:27,290
-What do you feel?

620
00:38:31,170 --> 00:38:31,910
-Just scared.

621
00:38:34,850 --> 00:38:36,370
Being sick in a
 way that makes me

622
00:38:36,370 --> 00:38:37,860
feel like it's
 already happening.

623
00:38:43,300 --> 00:38:50,260
And if I died now, on a gorgeous
 day like today, with you here,

624
00:38:50,260 --> 00:38:53,770
my life would have ended well.

625
00:38:53,770 --> 00:38:54,660
I love you.

626
00:39:25,540 --> 00:39:28,920
-What are you doing
 in here all alone?

627
00:39:28,920 --> 00:39:30,380
Are you being
 mysterious or exclusive?

628
00:39:35,370 --> 00:39:37,510
-Enigmatic.

629
00:39:37,510 --> 00:39:39,520
-Where's Lyle?

630
00:39:39,520 --> 00:39:43,440
-He's upstairs asleep.

631
00:39:43,440 --> 00:39:47,120
It's amazing how exhausting
 indolence can be.

632
00:39:47,120 --> 00:39:48,190
And Marian?

633
00:39:48,190 --> 00:39:52,390
-I think she's
 checking on Rowland.

634
00:39:52,390 --> 00:39:55,250
-Tony was my half brother.

635
00:39:55,250 --> 00:39:57,950
We had the same mother.

636
00:39:57,950 --> 00:40:00,490
He used to get all the girls.

637
00:40:00,490 --> 00:40:02,530
The only problem was
 he didn't want them.

638
00:40:07,250 --> 00:40:10,560
Well, I'd better get cleaned up.

639
00:40:10,560 --> 00:40:14,670
Um, I just wanted to say
 that Marian and I are

640
00:40:14,670 --> 00:40:18,650
very pleased that
 you're here, Robert.

641
00:40:18,650 --> 00:40:22,070
And very happy to
 see you with Lyle.

642
00:40:22,070 --> 00:40:24,040
-Thanks, John.

643
00:40:24,040 --> 00:40:27,790
I mean, maybe it should
 be awkward with Robert.

644
00:40:31,440 --> 00:40:31,940
-Is it?

645
00:40:35,520 --> 00:40:36,660
-Well, I can't
 pretend it doesn't

646
00:40:36,660 --> 00:40:38,070
make me feel a
 little uncomfortable.

647
00:40:51,730 --> 00:40:57,830
This last year has
 been unbearable.

648
00:40:57,830 --> 00:41:01,430
There were times I wish I'd had
 the strength to commit suicide.

649
00:41:04,160 --> 00:41:07,360
I guess if I'd had the strength,
 I wouldn't have felt the need.

650
00:41:07,360 --> 00:41:09,640
But even at my most
 desperate, I always

651
00:41:09,640 --> 00:41:12,700
thought something
 wonderful my happen.

652
00:41:12,700 --> 00:41:13,330
It wasn't optimism.

653
00:41:13,330 --> 00:41:17,520
It was just a respect
 for the possible.

654
00:41:17,520 --> 00:41:21,470
And then this boy walks into my
 life, and I feel human again.

655
00:41:25,250 --> 00:41:28,510
And I just wanted to
 share that with you.

656
00:41:28,510 --> 00:41:31,820
-Well, now, I feel awful.

657
00:41:31,820 --> 00:41:32,320
-Good.

658
00:41:35,990 --> 00:41:38,320
-How could I not say
 anything, because that

659
00:41:38,320 --> 00:41:40,860
would be dishonest.

660
00:41:40,860 --> 00:41:43,220
And you know me
 too well for that.

661
00:41:46,400 --> 00:41:48,290
And you are my best friend.

662
00:41:53,460 --> 00:41:57,230
-I don't know why I always feel
 like whispering when I'm here.

663
00:41:57,230 --> 00:42:02,070
The first time I saw this
 place, I nearly cried.

664
00:42:02,070 --> 00:42:04,030
-Well, you were always more
 sentimental about nature

665
00:42:04,030 --> 00:42:05,710
than people.

666
00:42:05,710 --> 00:42:09,200
-Well, God is in nature.

667
00:42:09,200 --> 00:42:11,250
-And truth is in wine.

668
00:42:11,250 --> 00:42:13,270
-Thierry seems very nice.

669
00:42:13,270 --> 00:42:14,740
-He's married.

670
00:42:14,740 --> 00:42:16,740
-Oh.

671
00:42:16,740 --> 00:42:20,020
Well, the nicest
 men often are, which

672
00:42:20,020 --> 00:42:25,030
probably means that they aren't
 quite as nice as they appear.

673
00:42:25,030 --> 00:42:26,630
-You never let that stop you.

674
00:42:29,290 --> 00:42:33,430
-Did you know he was married
 when you first met him?

675
00:42:33,430 --> 00:42:35,500
-It slipped his mind.

676
00:42:35,500 --> 00:42:38,400
-Yeah.

677
00:42:38,400 --> 00:42:40,050
His wife lives in France?

678
00:42:40,050 --> 00:42:40,830
-Santa Monica.

679
00:42:43,360 --> 00:42:45,030
Yeah, it's not really a
 matter of distance though.

680
00:42:47,860 --> 00:42:50,150
It really is lovely here.

681
00:42:50,150 --> 00:42:51,660
-Isn't it?

682
00:42:51,660 --> 00:42:55,050
-You know it's
 beautiful in Italy, too.

683
00:42:55,050 --> 00:42:57,390
Have you thought any more
 about that offer I made you?

684
00:42:57,390 --> 00:42:59,010
-What would I do in Italy?

685
00:42:59,010 --> 00:43:00,810
-They make movies
 in Italy, Nina.

686
00:43:00,810 --> 00:43:01,950
-Yeah, in Italian.

687
00:43:01,950 --> 00:43:03,140
-You speak Italian.

688
00:43:03,140 --> 00:43:05,870
-Used to.

689
00:43:05,870 --> 00:43:09,270
So is, uh, Tony's
 brother good looking?

690
00:43:09,270 --> 00:43:11,500
-I don't really
 remember, you know.

691
00:43:11,500 --> 00:43:14,150
He's just very, very quiet.

692
00:43:14,150 --> 00:43:20,370
His personality doesn't really
 quite extend out to its edges.

693
00:43:20,370 --> 00:43:22,800
His wife speaks her mind though.

694
00:43:22,800 --> 00:43:24,040
-They sound awful.

695
00:43:24,040 --> 00:43:25,510
-No, they really aren't so bad.

696
00:43:25,510 --> 00:43:26,700
They're just not his type.

697
00:43:26,700 --> 00:43:29,330
-You sound like such a snob.

698
00:43:29,330 --> 00:43:31,090
-Hey, you're the one that
 said they sounded so awful.

699
00:43:31,090 --> 00:43:32,310
-Can we go back now.

700
00:43:32,310 --> 00:43:35,120
I think I've have enough
 beauty for one day.

701
00:43:35,120 --> 00:43:35,620
-OK.

702
00:43:49,400 --> 00:43:51,310
-What do you think of Robert?

703
00:43:51,310 --> 00:43:52,600
-He's nice enough.

704
00:43:52,600 --> 00:43:54,460
He's young.

705
00:43:54,460 --> 00:43:55,960
How are you going to cook these?

706
00:43:55,960 --> 00:43:58,070
-We're going to saute them.

707
00:43:58,070 --> 00:43:58,970
-Hmm.

708
00:43:58,970 --> 00:44:00,760
-I don't like him.

709
00:44:00,760 --> 00:44:01,700
-Why not?

710
00:44:01,700 --> 00:44:04,520
-Just something about him.

711
00:44:04,520 --> 00:44:07,900
-It must be hard for
 him coming up here.

712
00:44:07,900 --> 00:44:11,710
So well in being
 so closed to Tony.

713
00:44:11,710 --> 00:44:13,020
-Oh, I understand that.

714
00:44:13,020 --> 00:44:15,290
It's just, I don't
 buy his enthusiasm.

715
00:44:15,290 --> 00:44:19,770
He seems presumptuous
 or judgmental.

716
00:44:25,970 --> 00:44:30,040
-Aren't you being just a
 little judgmental yourself?

717
00:44:30,040 --> 00:44:32,260
-We can't help but form
 impressions of people, can we?

718
00:44:43,640 --> 00:44:46,610
I don't think it will last.

719
00:44:46,610 --> 00:44:50,260
-Well, then you should be nice.

720
00:44:50,260 --> 00:44:52,230
If he's just something
 that Lyle's going through,

721
00:44:52,230 --> 00:44:53,600
you probably won't
 have to see him again.

722
00:44:56,200 --> 00:44:56,700
-Yeah.

723
00:45:06,840 --> 00:45:07,590
-A turban?

724
00:45:07,590 --> 00:45:11,060
-I thought we could use
 a little ammunition,

725
00:45:11,060 --> 00:45:13,950
I hope that thing works.

726
00:45:13,950 --> 00:45:16,650
-Don't you have somewhere to go?

727
00:45:16,650 --> 00:45:17,200
-I'm Italian.

728
00:45:17,200 --> 00:45:21,220
I'm expected to be late.

729
00:45:21,220 --> 00:45:22,940
-You know, I always
 thought that a grudge

730
00:45:22,940 --> 00:45:24,880
would make a person ugly.

731
00:45:24,880 --> 00:45:29,090
But that isn't true
 in your case, is it?

732
00:45:29,090 --> 00:45:30,360
Strange.

733
00:45:30,360 --> 00:45:31,970
-You can go anyplace
 in the world

734
00:45:31,970 --> 00:45:33,940
and some things remain constant.

735
00:45:33,940 --> 00:45:37,010
The sun goes up,
 the moon comes down

736
00:45:37,010 --> 00:45:41,600
and children resent
 their parents.

737
00:45:41,600 --> 00:45:43,660
-You wear too much
 makeup, Mother.

738
00:45:43,660 --> 00:45:46,520
In this light, you look
 like a beautiful prostitute.

739
00:45:46,520 --> 00:45:49,850
-You know, one thing that
 is disturbing about children

740
00:45:49,850 --> 00:45:52,520
is that they can always see
 right through their parents.

741
00:45:52,520 --> 00:45:55,050
What they don't realize,
 is their parents

742
00:45:55,050 --> 00:45:58,950
can see right through them back.

743
00:45:58,950 --> 00:45:59,900
-Nina, take the wine.

744
00:46:02,510 --> 00:46:03,740
You're too much.

745
00:46:03,740 --> 00:46:05,690
-It doesn't matter, Thierry.

746
00:46:05,690 --> 00:46:06,890
I should get going anyway.

747
00:46:06,890 --> 00:46:08,410
-You look very beautiful.

748
00:46:08,410 --> 00:46:09,220
-Thank you.

749
00:46:09,220 --> 00:46:10,450
-Have a nice evening.

750
00:46:10,450 --> 00:46:10,970
-Thank you.

751
00:46:40,070 --> 00:46:41,550
-Hey.

752
00:46:41,550 --> 00:46:43,030
-Hi.

753
00:46:43,030 --> 00:46:43,530
-Hi.

754
00:46:43,530 --> 00:46:44,510
How are you?

755
00:46:44,510 --> 00:46:46,480
I'll be done in just a minute.

756
00:46:51,410 --> 00:46:54,860
-Where did Tony die?

757
00:46:54,860 --> 00:46:55,360
-What?

758
00:46:58,330 --> 00:47:02,770
-It was here in this
 house, wasn't it?

759
00:47:02,770 --> 00:47:07,570
-Robert, I don't think
 that's a question to really--

760
00:47:07,570 --> 00:47:09,530
-True.

761
00:47:09,530 --> 00:47:11,360
-Robert, it doesn't matter.

762
00:47:11,360 --> 00:47:14,020
Of course, it fucking matters.

763
00:47:14,020 --> 00:47:16,440
-Robert, please.

764
00:47:16,440 --> 00:47:16,970
-Tell me.

765
00:47:30,830 --> 00:47:32,730
-Jesus.

766
00:47:32,730 --> 00:47:34,540
-My daughter, Nina,
 came up from the city

767
00:47:34,540 --> 00:47:36,880
unexpectedly, so it kind
 of slowed things down.

768
00:47:36,880 --> 00:47:37,430
-Hello.

769
00:47:37,430 --> 00:47:37,930
-Hello.

770
00:47:37,930 --> 00:47:39,040
-You remember my husband?

771
00:47:39,040 --> 00:47:41,040
-Yes, how are you?

772
00:47:41,040 --> 00:47:42,650
-You should have brought
 your daughter with you.

773
00:47:42,650 --> 00:47:46,170
-Yes, I-- oh, my word.

774
00:47:46,170 --> 00:47:47,240
What lovely paintings.

775
00:47:47,240 --> 00:47:49,470
-Yes, Marian painted them.

776
00:47:49,470 --> 00:47:50,400
-Really?

777
00:47:50,400 --> 00:47:53,520
Well, if you cook half
 as well as you paint,

778
00:47:53,520 --> 00:47:55,240
we're in for a rare treat.

779
00:47:55,240 --> 00:47:56,740
-Can I get you
 something to drink?

780
00:47:56,740 --> 00:47:58,380
-Absolutely.

781
00:47:58,380 --> 00:47:59,120
-Red wine?

782
00:47:59,120 --> 00:48:00,430
-Red, please.

783
00:48:00,430 --> 00:48:01,860
-OK.

784
00:48:01,860 --> 00:48:04,120
-Now what should we
 do about Nina, is it?

785
00:48:04,120 --> 00:48:05,440
-Oh, nothing, she's just fine.

786
00:48:05,440 --> 00:48:06,730
She's here with her fiance.

787
00:48:06,730 --> 00:48:08,100
-Well, you should have
 brought them both.

788
00:48:08,100 --> 00:48:10,220
-Why don't you give them a call?

789
