01:00:17,200 --> 01:00:18,770
-Well, I've already eaten.

1047
01:00:18,770 --> 01:00:21,250
I'm just here for the
 company and the alcohol.

1048
01:00:21,250 --> 01:00:22,800
I'll start with a beer.

1049
01:00:22,800 --> 01:00:23,880
-So where's Thierry?

1050
01:00:23,880 --> 01:00:25,270
-He had to go back to the city.

1051
01:00:25,270 --> 01:00:26,750
You must be Marian.

1052
01:00:26,750 --> 01:00:27,250
I'm Nina.

1053
01:00:27,250 --> 01:00:27,750
-Hello.

1054
01:00:27,750 --> 01:00:29,170
-I've heard all about you.

1055
01:00:29,170 --> 01:00:32,710
-This is Lyle and
 Robert, his friend.

1056
01:00:32,710 --> 01:00:34,490
-His lover.

1057
01:00:34,490 --> 01:00:36,140
-What did I tell you?

1058
01:00:39,110 --> 01:00:40,790
-What did she tell you?

1059
01:00:40,790 --> 01:00:42,600
That all of the men
 that I find attractive

1060
01:00:42,600 --> 01:00:47,350
are either gay, like these two,
 or Tony, or married like John.

1061
01:00:47,350 --> 01:00:49,770
-Your mother said
 you were engaged.

1062
01:00:49,770 --> 01:00:52,760
-Did she?

1063
01:00:52,760 --> 01:00:56,950
Well, Thierry was, was being the
 operative word, my boyfriend.

1064
01:00:56,950 --> 01:00:59,120
And we were saying a
 less than tearful goodbye

1065
01:00:59,120 --> 01:01:00,900
when your gallant
 husband arrived.

1066
01:01:00,900 --> 01:01:02,010
-Oh.

1067
01:01:02,010 --> 01:01:05,220
-Well, maybe my gallant husband
 could help me in the kitchen.

1068
01:01:13,250 --> 01:01:16,120
Gallant, my ass.

1069
01:01:16,120 --> 01:01:18,400
-You mentioned Tony.

1070
01:01:18,400 --> 01:01:19,100
Tony Kerr.

1071
01:01:19,100 --> 01:01:20,050
Did you know him?

1072
01:01:20,050 --> 01:01:21,550
-Yeah, I used to very well.

1073
01:01:21,550 --> 01:01:23,760
We went to Morocco together.

1074
01:01:23,760 --> 01:01:27,330
-You went to Morocco
 with Tony Kerr?

1075
01:01:27,330 --> 01:01:27,990
-Yeah.

1076
01:01:27,990 --> 01:01:31,930
When I was 18, right
 after boarding school.

1077
01:01:31,930 --> 01:01:34,490
-Wait, I was there, too.

1078
01:01:34,490 --> 01:01:35,200
-With Tony?

1079
01:01:35,200 --> 01:01:37,080
-Did you stay at the--

1080
01:01:37,080 --> 01:01:38,200
-Aahana Hotel.

1081
01:01:38,200 --> 01:01:39,120
-Yeah.

1082
01:01:39,120 --> 01:01:40,960
-Hotel.

1083
01:01:40,960 --> 01:01:45,650
Oh, we used to sit naked
 and read Joe Orton together.

1084
01:01:45,650 --> 01:01:47,360
-Yeah.

1085
01:01:47,360 --> 01:01:50,540
-I had no idea he had died.

1086
01:01:50,540 --> 01:01:52,180
-Well, I hadn't either.

1087
01:01:52,180 --> 01:01:55,500
-He died here in this house.

1088
01:01:55,500 --> 01:01:59,140
-Oh, well, this is
 no topic for dinner.

1089
01:01:59,140 --> 01:02:00,750
-No, it's fine, really.

1090
01:02:00,750 --> 01:02:05,340
-Well, I meant-- never mind.

1091
01:02:05,340 --> 01:02:07,420
-She look's like she just
 got out of the Navy the way

1092
01:02:07,420 --> 01:02:08,540
she's looking at you.

1093
01:02:11,540 --> 01:02:15,630
-Well, everything looks
 just delicious Marian.

1094
01:02:19,590 --> 01:02:23,390
-Lyle, I was reading a review
 of your book in the "Times".

1095
01:02:23,390 --> 01:02:25,140
I found it very interesting.

1096
01:02:25,140 --> 01:02:27,660
I tried to get a copy, but
 the book stores up here

1097
01:02:27,660 --> 01:02:28,900
are just hopeless.

1098
01:02:28,900 --> 01:02:30,630
-Well, I'm sure I've got
 an extra copy somewhere,

1099
01:02:30,630 --> 01:02:33,630
and I could sign it for you
 before you go if you'd like.

1100
01:02:33,630 --> 01:02:34,730
-Really, that
 would be very nice.

1101
01:02:34,730 --> 01:02:35,770
Thank you.
 -What's it called?

1102
01:02:35,770 --> 01:02:37,180
Neo This, Neo That.

1103
01:02:37,180 --> 01:02:40,030
-Oh, that's the
 story of my life.

1104
01:02:40,030 --> 01:02:41,550
Here, to a happy weekend.

1105
01:02:46,050 --> 01:02:47,860
-My mother's writing a book.

1106
01:02:47,860 --> 01:02:48,630
-Really?

1107
01:02:48,630 --> 01:02:49,430
What about?

1108
01:02:49,430 --> 01:02:50,450
My late husband.

1109
01:02:50,450 --> 01:02:53,350
Nina's stepfather,
 Atorian Ponti.

1110
01:02:53,350 --> 01:02:54,420
-The architect?

1111
01:02:54,420 --> 01:02:54,920
-Yes.

1112
01:02:54,920 --> 01:02:55,870
You've heard of him?

1113
01:02:55,870 --> 01:02:57,300
-Of course.

1114
01:02:57,300 --> 01:02:59,030
He's one of the greatest
 European architects

1115
01:02:59,030 --> 01:02:59,560
of this century.

1116
01:02:59,560 --> 01:03:02,210
-It's a pity his work never
 caught on in the United States.

1117
01:03:02,210 --> 01:03:04,100
-I guess he was just
 too much of a maverick.

1118
01:03:04,100 --> 01:03:05,370
-Yes, he was a maverick.

1119
01:03:05,370 --> 01:03:06,840
-I think he was a genius.

1120
01:03:06,840 --> 01:03:07,920
-So do I.

1121
01:03:07,920 --> 01:03:10,600
-I would love to read your
 book when it's finished.

1122
01:03:10,600 --> 01:03:14,010
-Well, I'm afraid it's not
 going forward very quickly.

1123
01:03:14,010 --> 01:03:16,850
I guess I've just bitten
 off more than I can chew.

1124
01:03:16,850 --> 01:03:19,980
Atorian is so rich
 and contrast, it's

1125
01:03:19,980 --> 01:03:21,990
really hard to
 capture him in words.

1126
01:03:21,990 --> 01:03:22,970
-Excuse me.

1127
01:03:27,360 --> 01:03:29,800
-Where are you going?

1128
01:03:29,800 --> 01:03:32,360
-I left my wallet
 down by the wall.

1129
01:03:32,360 --> 01:03:35,240
-Well, it's not going anywhere.

1130
01:03:35,240 --> 01:03:36,710
-Be right back.

1131
01:03:50,050 --> 01:03:51,280
-I don't know, pretty
 soon he's going

1132
01:03:51,280 --> 01:03:53,800
to start sleeping
 by that damn wall.

1133
01:03:53,800 --> 01:03:55,320
-Well, let him.

1134
01:03:55,320 --> 01:03:56,920
One thing I've
 learned in my life

1135
01:03:56,920 --> 01:03:59,130
is to let men sleep
 where they want to.

1136
01:04:04,680 --> 01:04:06,770
So Robert, you
 don't know anything

1137
01:04:06,770 --> 01:04:10,450
about restoration
 of canvases and--

1138
01:04:10,450 --> 01:04:14,400
-Marian did that for
 several years at the Met.

1139
01:04:14,400 --> 01:04:14,900
-Really?

1140
01:04:14,900 --> 01:04:15,750
Well, I didn't know that.

1141
01:04:15,750 --> 01:04:18,160
That's very interesting.

1142
01:04:18,160 --> 01:04:21,400
Have you restored old
 canvases and things?

1143
01:04:21,400 --> 01:04:21,900
-Um-hmm.

1144
01:04:21,900 --> 01:04:25,440
-How about frescoes, which is
 what I'm really getting at?

1145
01:04:25,440 --> 01:04:25,970
-Only canvasses.

1146
01:04:25,970 --> 01:04:27,480
Why do you ask?

1147
01:04:27,480 --> 01:04:31,170
-I'm doing some work
 on my house in Italy.

1148
01:04:31,170 --> 01:04:33,200
And we ran across some frescoes.

1149
01:04:33,200 --> 01:04:36,020
They're very badly
 damaged, but I

1150
01:04:36,020 --> 01:04:37,610
would love to have
 them restored.

1151
01:04:37,610 --> 01:04:38,880
-That must feel like a miracle.

1152
01:04:38,880 --> 01:04:41,270
-It does.

1153
01:04:41,270 --> 01:04:43,830
-Just digging in the
 ground and there they are.

1154
01:04:43,830 --> 01:04:44,330
-Yes.

1155
01:04:44,330 --> 01:04:46,020
-Are they beautiful?

1156
01:04:46,020 --> 01:04:47,550
-Oh, I think so.

1157
01:04:47,550 --> 01:04:49,490
I mean, I don't know whether
 Atorian would have thought

1158
01:04:49,490 --> 01:04:53,720
really, but I think
 they're very beautiful.

1159
01:04:53,720 --> 01:04:56,040
Well, I could certainly get some
 names of someone if you want.

1160
01:04:56,040 --> 01:04:58,450
I mean, you hate to
 go to all that trouble

1161
01:04:58,450 --> 01:05:01,430
and have them turn
 out second rate.

1162
01:05:05,690 --> 01:05:08,710
-I wouldn't want you
 to go to any trouble.

1163
01:05:08,710 --> 01:05:12,400
-Oh, it wouldn't be a trouble.

1164
01:05:23,530 --> 01:05:25,710
-Lyle, could you go
 see where John is.

1165
01:05:25,710 --> 01:05:27,090
His food's getting cold.

1166
01:05:27,090 --> 01:05:28,150
-I'll go.

1167
01:05:28,150 --> 01:05:28,650
-Nina.

1168
01:05:31,260 --> 01:05:32,920
-It makes much
 more sense if I go.

1169
01:05:32,920 --> 01:05:37,160
I've already eaten, so
 which way is this, uh, wall.

1170
01:05:37,160 --> 01:05:38,490
-You might get lost down there.

1171
01:05:38,490 --> 01:05:40,560
I think he's created
 a bit of a maze.

1172
01:05:40,560 --> 01:05:45,360
Well, I have an unerring
 sense of direction as long

1173
01:05:45,360 --> 01:05:47,720
as I know where I'm going.

1174
01:05:47,720 --> 01:05:49,400
-It's just across the lawn.

1175
01:05:49,400 --> 01:05:51,620
There's a little pathway
 above the trees to the right.

1176
01:06:15,320 --> 01:06:19,960
-Did you know the word, crochet
 comes from the old French word

1177
01:06:19,960 --> 01:06:24,540
croak, meaning, say
 your prayers, rabbit.

1178
01:06:24,540 --> 01:06:26,360
-Oh, no, no.

1179
01:06:26,360 --> 01:06:29,550
It comes from the old
 Gaelic word [GAELIC],

1180
01:06:29,550 --> 01:06:31,720
which means leave my
 ball alone you lying,

1181
01:06:31,720 --> 01:06:34,360
cheating, sick bastard.

1182
01:06:38,600 --> 01:06:40,530
-Can we play doubles?

1183
01:06:40,530 --> 01:06:44,600
No, no, because
 then Lyle and Marian

1184
01:06:44,600 --> 01:06:46,620
will be discussing
 postmodernism,

1185
01:06:46,620 --> 01:06:49,700
and I can only take so much
 deconstruction in one weekend.

1186
01:06:52,520 --> 01:06:54,400
Hmm.

1187
01:06:54,400 --> 01:06:56,540
Sometimes I wish I'd
 been born lucky instead

1188
01:06:56,540 --> 01:06:59,540
of handsome and talented.

1189
01:06:59,540 --> 01:07:02,310
-It's funny.

1190
01:07:02,310 --> 01:07:05,140
I always thought you
 were the lucky one.

1191
01:07:05,140 --> 01:07:06,890
-Compared to you?

1192
01:07:06,890 --> 01:07:07,680
It's all relative.

1193
01:07:14,880 --> 01:07:20,230
-You know, you can stay
 here as long as you like.

1194
01:07:20,230 --> 01:07:22,810
-Maybe it's like a vacation.

1195
01:07:22,810 --> 01:07:25,340
-What is?

1196
01:07:25,340 --> 01:07:27,860
You know how when
 you're on holiday,

1197
01:07:27,860 --> 01:07:30,030
you pretend you're
 having such a great time,

1198
01:07:30,030 --> 01:07:35,500
but then towards the end, you
 just, you want to get home,

1199
01:07:35,500 --> 01:07:39,070
sleep in your own bed
 with your pillows.

1200
01:07:39,070 --> 01:07:40,270
Maybe life's like that.

1201
01:07:43,680 --> 01:07:46,500
Whoa, what hit me?

1202
01:07:46,500 --> 01:07:47,230
-Last martini, mate.

1203
01:07:52,080 --> 01:07:53,050
-All right.

1204
01:07:59,360 --> 01:08:01,300
Hey.

1205
01:08:01,300 --> 01:08:03,520
I'm poison.

1206
01:08:03,520 --> 01:08:04,220
I'm poison.

1207
01:08:15,900 --> 01:08:17,210
-Sorry, the door was open.

1208
01:08:22,030 --> 01:08:26,210
-So whole circus coming,
 or is it just us?

1209
01:08:26,210 --> 01:08:27,700
-It's just us.

1210
01:08:31,170 --> 01:08:34,140
Did you make this?

1211
01:08:34,140 --> 01:08:34,640
-Yeah.

1212
01:08:38,140 --> 01:08:39,150
-It's amazing.

1213
01:08:39,150 --> 01:08:39,650
-Thanks.

1214
01:08:42,620 --> 01:08:47,900
I was just thinking what
 I was going to build next.

1215
01:08:47,900 --> 01:08:50,520
Something big right
 out in the middle

1216
01:08:50,520 --> 01:08:52,490
of the lake with
 about two feet of it

1217
01:08:52,490 --> 01:08:55,350
sticking above the surface.

1218
01:08:55,350 --> 01:08:58,110
-Something you can
 only see from below.

1219
01:08:58,110 --> 01:08:58,610
-Yeah.

1220
01:09:01,580 --> 01:09:03,010
-I like that.

1221
01:09:08,730 --> 01:09:12,800
We should go back.

1222
01:09:12,800 --> 01:09:15,370
-You just got here.

1223
01:09:15,370 --> 01:09:16,360
Sit down.

1224
01:09:33,710 --> 01:09:36,980
-Two people sitting side by
 side on a rocking good night.

1225
01:09:39,980 --> 01:09:42,280
We're as good as guilty already.

1226
01:10:13,300 --> 01:10:15,050
You're not dull.

1227
01:10:36,610 --> 01:10:39,050
-Hmm.

1228
01:10:39,050 --> 01:10:40,220
-Violence gathers
 in a small place.

1229
01:10:43,190 --> 01:10:46,660
A room, a bed, a glove.

1230
01:10:46,660 --> 01:10:49,120
-What's that?

1231
01:10:49,120 --> 01:10:51,920
-That's the infant Jesus
 of Prague, James Schuyler.

1232
01:10:55,240 --> 01:10:56,150
-I don't think I like it.

1233
01:10:56,150 --> 01:10:58,210
-It's the most wonderful thing.

1234
01:10:58,210 --> 01:10:59,310
-It sounds like a threat.

1235
01:11:02,790 --> 01:11:03,930
-More like a warning.

1236
01:11:14,010 --> 01:11:17,990
-What am I going to do with you?

1237
01:11:17,990 --> 01:11:20,140
-Hey, what am I going
 to do without you?

1238
01:11:20,140 --> 01:11:23,120
-Get on with your life.

1239
01:11:23,120 --> 01:11:25,200
You don't need to
 know what you want.

1240
01:11:25,200 --> 01:11:27,110
You just need to know
 what you don't want.

1241
01:11:27,110 --> 01:11:29,270
-I don't want you to keep
 trying to cheer me up.

1242
01:11:29,270 --> 01:11:29,770
-Hey.

1243
01:11:44,300 --> 01:11:49,010
Times like this you
 have to figure out

1244
01:11:49,010 --> 01:11:53,150
what it is about life
 that still delights you.

1245
01:11:53,150 --> 01:11:56,070
Then grab a hold of it.

1246
01:11:56,070 --> 01:11:58,720
Grow claws if you have
 to, but just don't let go.

1247
01:12:07,870 --> 01:12:09,320
You delight me.

1248
01:12:24,500 --> 01:12:28,250
-All the anodized aluminum,
 but that is if they let me.

1249
01:12:28,250 --> 01:12:31,570
The Italian government is
 just impossible sometimes.

1250
01:12:31,570 --> 01:12:33,390
You can't even
 clean out a closet

1251
01:12:33,390 --> 01:12:36,120
without their permission.

1252
01:12:36,120 --> 01:12:38,020
-Yeah, but you really
 got to hand to them.

1253
01:12:38,020 --> 01:12:40,330
They've kept their
 country really beautiful.

1254
01:12:40,330 --> 01:12:42,810
-Yeah, they have, haven't they?

1255
01:12:42,810 --> 01:12:45,820
Well, I'm going to
 ask you something,

1256
01:12:45,820 --> 01:12:48,080
and just answer me honestly.

1257
01:12:48,080 --> 01:12:51,330
Are you a good painter?

1258
01:12:51,330 --> 01:12:53,240
-I think I am.

1259
01:12:53,240 --> 01:12:54,200
Yes.

1260
01:12:54,200 --> 01:12:56,770
I admit I am.

1261
01:12:56,770 --> 01:12:59,080
All right, then, I want
 to make you an offer.

1262
01:12:59,080 --> 01:13:02,180
You know those I have
 that need restoring?

1263
01:13:02,180 --> 01:13:05,330
Why don't you come and do them?

1264
01:13:05,330 --> 01:13:07,480
-Oh, I, I don't really
 know a lot about frescoes.

1265
01:13:07,480 --> 01:13:08,750
Oh, you can learn.

1266
01:13:08,750 --> 01:13:09,990
I'm sure you can.

1267
01:13:09,990 --> 01:13:12,820
I mean, I'd pay you,
 of course, and there's

1268
01:13:12,820 --> 01:13:15,200
a very nice little apartment
 right on the grounds.

1269
01:13:15,200 --> 01:13:17,580
-I don't know what to say.

1270
01:13:17,580 --> 01:13:20,040
-Well, think about it.

1271
01:13:20,040 --> 01:13:21,480
-Love at first sight.

1272
01:13:21,480 --> 01:13:24,150
-My mother's always been
 a sucker for artists.

1273
01:13:24,150 --> 01:13:26,860
-Ah, put it on your head.

1274
01:13:26,860 --> 01:13:27,690
You'd be Carmen Miranda.

1275
01:13:27,690 --> 01:13:29,150
-Too beautiful to eat.

1276
01:13:33,540 --> 01:13:34,700
-Oh, Robert.

1277
01:13:34,700 --> 01:13:35,800
Here.

1278
01:13:35,800 --> 01:13:36,950
They're grape scissors.

1279
01:13:36,950 --> 01:13:39,570
We use them to cut a bunch.

1280
01:13:39,570 --> 01:13:42,950
Take a branch and cut
 the stem like this.

1281
01:13:42,950 --> 01:13:45,370
Not difficult.

1282
01:13:45,370 --> 01:13:47,300
-Go ahead, Robert.

1283
01:13:47,300 --> 01:13:49,690
-Oh, for heaven's
 sakes, don't tame him.

1284
01:13:49,690 --> 01:13:53,780
Let him eat grapes with
 his fingers if he wants to.

1285
01:13:53,780 --> 01:13:56,500
Let's all rid ourselves of
 these ridiculous, ridiculous,

1286
01:13:56,500 --> 01:13:58,980
ridiculous affectations.

1287
01:14:04,930 --> 01:14:06,910
-They were my grandmothers.

1288
01:14:16,830 --> 01:14:19,310
-I didn't mean any harm.

1289
01:14:19,310 --> 01:14:22,150
-That's when you usually
 do the most damage.

1290
01:14:22,150 --> 01:14:23,070
-I'll go talk to her.

1291
01:14:23,070 --> 01:14:23,570
-No, no.

1292
01:14:23,570 --> 01:14:26,850
I, I've broken something here.

1293
01:14:26,850 --> 01:14:29,570
It's up to me to put it right.

1294
01:14:29,570 --> 01:14:30,530
Oh, dear.

1295
01:14:35,840 --> 01:14:38,150
-I'm going for a walk.

1296
01:14:38,150 --> 01:14:39,310
-I'll come with you.

1297
01:14:44,420 --> 01:14:48,050
Marian, I am so sorry.

1298
01:14:48,050 --> 01:14:48,710
-I'm sorry.

1299
01:14:48,710 --> 01:14:51,750
-Oh, no, you have nothing
 to be sorry about.

1300
01:14:51,750 --> 01:14:55,060
I just, I know you want this
 to be a special evening,

1301
